{"title_page": "Karla Woisnitza", "text_new": "'''Karla Woisnitza''' (born 16 August 1952) is a German artist.\n\n== Life ==\nWoisnitza was born in [[R\u00fcdersdorf]]. Before she went to art school, she took part in a drawing group in her hometown led by the artist [[Erika St\u00fcrmer-Alex]]. She studied set design from 1973 to 1979 at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]]. In her core curriculum, she studied with G\u00fcnter Hornig, who was an inspiration to a number of influential performance artists in East Germany<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Performance art in the second public sphere : event-based art in late socialist Europe|others=Cseh-Varga, Katalin,, Czirak, Adam|isbn=978-1-351-75708-9|location=Oxon|oclc=1022784997}}</ref> and who gave his students room for creative experimentation despite the conservative climate of the academy.<ref name=\":0\" /> During her studies, Woisnitza brought together women artists and founded loose networks.<ref name=\":1\" /> These included her fellow students and upcoming artists like [[Christine Schlegel]], [[Marie-Luise Bauerschmidt]], [[Sabine Gumnitz]], [[Monika Hanske]], [[Cornelia Schleime]], [[Angela Schumann]]. They realized a number of collective events together.<ref name=\":1\" /> These informal performances involved body actions, such as ''Face Painting Action (Gesichts-malaktion'', 1978\u20131979).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1991, Woisnitza received a diploma in painting and graphic design from the Academy. In 1992, she received the {{ill|Marianne Werefkin Prize|de|Marianne-Werefkin-Preis}} from the {{ill|Berlin Women Artist Association|de|Verein der Berliner K\u00fcnstlerinnen}}. From 1993 to 1995, she painted seven large [[fresco]]es for the Virchow-Klinikum campus of the [[Charit\u00e9]] hospital in [[Berlin]]. In 1994, Woisnitza received the [[K\u00e4the Kollwitz Prize]] from the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|Berlin Academy of Arts]]. In 2002, she created a fresco for the church hall of the Evangelical church in R\u00fcdersdorf.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://galerie-elfenau.ch/kuenstler/karla-woisnitza/ |title=Woisnitza, Karla |publisher=Galerie Elfenau |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://clara.nmwa.org/index.php?g=entity_detail&entity_id=12529 |title=Karla Woisnitza |work=Clara Database of Women Artists}}</ref>\n\nWoisnitza was encouraged by two artist/teachers, Gunther Hornig and Erika Sturmer-Alex to do non-conformist conceptual art.  She developed \"an artistic activation of the body in the interest of female self-assurance and empowerment\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Medea Insurrection: Radical Women Artists Behind the Iron Curtain|publisher=Wende Museum|year=2019|isbn=|location=Culver City, California|pages=206}}</ref> and would call \"into question traditional representations of femininity as well as the basic difference between internal and external perception.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woisnitza, Karla}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German women painters]]\n[[Category:Fresco painters]]\n[[Category:German printmakers]]\n[[Category:Women book artists]]\n[[Category:German performance artists]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcdersdorf]]\n[[Category:21st-century German women artists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Karla Woisnitza''' (born 16 August 1952) is a German artist.\n\n== Life ==\nWoisnitza was born in [[R\u00fcdersdorf]]. Before she went to art school, she took part in a drawing group in her hometown led by the artist [[Erika St\u00fcrmer-Alex]]. She studied set design from 1973 to 1979 at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]]. In her core curriculum, she studied with G\u00fcnter Hornig, who was an inspiration to a number of influential performance artists in East Germany<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Performance art in the second public sphere : event-based art in late socialist Europe|others=Cseh-Varga, Katalin,, Czirak, Adam|isbn=978-1-351-75708-9|location=Oxon|oclc=1022784997}}</ref> and who gave his students room for creative experimentation despite the conservative climate of the academy.<ref name=\":0\" /> During her studies, Woisnitza brought together women artists and founded loose networks.<ref name=\":1\" /> These included her fellow students and upcoming artists like [[Christine Schlegel]] and [[Erika St\u00fcrmer-Alex]]. They realized a number of collective events together.<ref name=\":1\" /> These informal performances involved body actions, such as ''Face Painting Action (Gesichts-malaktion'', 1978\u20131979).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1991, Woisnitza received a diploma in painting and graphic design from the Academy. In 1992, she received the {{ill|Marianne Werefkin Prize|de|Marianne-Werefkin-Preis}} from the {{ill|Berlin Women Artist Association|de|Verein der Berliner K\u00fcnstlerinnen}}. From 1993 to 1995, she painted seven large [[fresco]]es for the Virchow-Klinikum campus of the [[Charit\u00e9]] hospital in [[Berlin]]. In 1994, Woisnitza received the [[K\u00e4the Kollwitz Prize]] from the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|Berlin Academy of Arts]]. In 2002, she created a fresco for the church hall of the Evangelical church in R\u00fcdersdorf.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://galerie-elfenau.ch/kuenstler/karla-woisnitza/ |title=Woisnitza, Karla |publisher=Galerie Elfenau |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://clara.nmwa.org/index.php?g=entity_detail&entity_id=12529 |title=Karla Woisnitza |work=Clara Database of Women Artists}}</ref>\n\nWoisnitza was encouraged by two artist/teachers, Gunther Hornig and Erika Sturmer-Alex to do non-conformist conceptual art.  She developed \"an artistic activation of the body in the interest of female self-assurance and empowerment\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Medea Insurrection: Radical Women Artists Behind the Iron Curtain|publisher=Wende Museum|year=2019|isbn=|location=Culver City, California|pages=206}}</ref> and would call \"into question traditional representations of femininity as well as the basic difference between internal and external perception.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woisnitza, Karla}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German women painters]]\n[[Category:Fresco painters]]\n[[Category:German printmakers]]\n[[Category:Women book artists]]\n[[Category:German performance artists]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcdersdorf]]\n[[Category:21st-century German women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Lehrche", "label": "safe", "comment": "The name Erika St\u00fcrmer-Alex at that place is a mistake. New are all participants of face painting action - all of them woman artists.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karla_Woisnitza"}
